				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${ }tf\left( {t,d} \right) = f_{t,d}$$\end{document}tft,d=ft,d

Next, we calculate idf(t,D). Assume that the single word apple appears in five of the 100 articles. According to (2), the idf(t,D) of apple is approximately 1.22184.2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{idf}}\left( {{\text{t}},{\text{D}}} \right) = \log \frac{N}{{1 + \left| {\left\{ {d \in D:t \in d} \right\}} \right|}}$$\end{document}idft,D=logN1+d∈D:t∈d

The TF-IDF of apple in article d is calculated using tf(t,d) and idf(t,D). According to (3), the tfidf(t,d,D) = 0.3333 × 1.22184 = 0.407 for apple in article d.3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
